            <ArticleTitle>Highly Efficient Removal of Thorium in Strong HNO3 Media Using A Novel Polymer Adsorbent Bearing Phosphonic Acid Ligand: A Combined Experimental and Density Functional Theory Study.</ArticleTitle>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1021/acsami.9b03674</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>It is an important task to develop the technologies for the extraction of thorium from stong HNO3 media with high efficiency. In this work, solvothermal polymerization of trimethylolpropane trimethacrylate (TRIM) and vinylphosphonic acid (VPA) has been used to synthesize a novel polymer material P (TRIM-VPA) bearing phosphonic acid ligand for thorium extrapment in strong HNO3 media. Under the current experiment condition, the polymer adsorbents showed a record-breaking maximum adsorption capacity for thorium (403.2 mg g-1) with an excellent selectivity for thorium over Gd (III), Nd (III), Ce (III), Sr (III), Sm (III) and La (III) in 4 M HNO3 media at 298 K. The content of P=O ligands existing on P (TRIM-VPA) has an obvious influence on the adsorption capacity for thorium. Increasing the content of P=O ligands would result in higher adsorption capacity of thorium. The isotherma data fitted well the Langmuir model and the sorption kinetic fitted the Pseudo-second-order model. The adsorption behavior was not only spontaneous, but also endothermic in reality. Both XPS and FTIR studies revealed that the adsorption interaction for thorium extraction was acquired only via the coordination of P=O groups anchored on P (TRIM-VPA) with thorium. Moreover, P (TRIM-VPA) still had high adsorption capacity after five sorption-desorption cycles in 4 M HNO3 media. DFT calculation suggested 1:2 ratio of Th (IV) with P=O group on the same graft chain validated the exerperimental findings. Thus, solvothermal polymerization method might be a promising way for the synthesis of the adsorbents for the highly efficient extraction of thorium from strong HNO3 media.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
